---

2. Fetch the JSON in your JavaScript
Inside your main JS file (or <script> tag in your HTML), paste this code:

`js
let questions = {};

function loadQuestions() {
  fetch("questions.json")
    .then(res => res.json())
    .then(data => {
      questions = data;
      startExam(); // call your exam start function
    })
    .catch(err => console.error("Error loading questions:", err));
}
`

---

3. Call it when exam starts
In your startExam() function, instead of hardcoding questions, just call:

`js
function startExam() {
  showScreen("screen-cbt");
  loadQuestions(); // loads from questions.json
}
`

---

✅ What You Just Did
- Created questions.json → holds your JAMB‑style questions.  
- Fetched it with JavaScript → loads them into your exam engine.  
- Displayed them in your existing HTML structure → .q-text and .options-list show the questions and answers.  

---

👉 This way, you don’t touch your Firebase auth or dashboard logic at all. You just add one file (questions.json) and a small fetch function.  

